Catalysis is a key driver of drug discovery and manufacture by providing unique routes to molecular targets and reducing energy consumption and waste. For decades, precious metals such as rhodium, iridium and palladium have dominated the catalyst landscape and while effective, are unattractive due to their high costs and environmental footprints. During the past period of NSF support, the intellectual merit of our collaborative program was focused on the discovery of catalysts based on earth-abundant metals such as cobalt for the most utilized chemical reactions in the synthesis of drug molecules. One notable achievement was the asymmetric hydrogenation of an indazole-containing enamide used in the synthesis of zajevepant, a first in-class intranasal treatment for migraine headaches. Not only does the cobalt catalyst eliminate precious metals used previously but also shortens the number of synthetic steps to the final drug target resulting in a significant reduction of waste in the overall process. Another notable feature of the cobalt- catalyzed reaction is the ability to generate catalysts from two different oxidation states separated by one-electron, an attribute absent with precious metals. Significant effort was also devoted to understanding how the cobalt catalysts operate. A comprehensive picture was developed that illuminates how the substrate molecules interact with the metal catalyst and are ultimately transformed into a single-handed product. These findings will accelerate future catalyst discovery by providing the necessary design principles to improve both reactivity and selectivity. Efforts were also made to expand the types of reactions enabled by earth-abundant metals to expand their scope and translation in drug discovery. By studying the interaction of visible light with air-stable and readily prepared cobalt compounds a new method for the conversion of commodity alkenes into value-added alcohols was discovered. This reaction proved both general and tolerant of many of the functional groups typically found in bioactive molecules. Accomplishments in broader impacts derived from the academic-industrial interface of the collaborative project and included more environmentally benign and sustainable methods in chemical synthesis, a unique training environment for graduate and undergraduate researchers and an emphasis on increasing participation from underrepresented groups.

